ertainment industry\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=[[Screen Actors Guild]]|publisher=[[SAG-AFTRA]]|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=January 30, 2016 |title=52nd Lifetime Achievement recipient Carol Burnett |accessdate=January 30, 2016|url=http://sagawards.org/awards/life-achievement-award-recipient/52nd}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Grammy Award]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album|Best Spoken Word Album]]\n|[[In Such Good Company|''In Such Good Company: Eleven Years Of Laughter, Mayhem, And Fun In The Sandbox'']]\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|title=59th Annual Grammy Awards|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/carol-burnett}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Peabody Award]]\n| Career Achievement Award\n| Achievements in her career\n| Herself\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/peabody-career-achievement-award-carol-burnett-presented-by-mercedes-benz|title=Career Achievement Award: Carol Burnett|work=[[Peabody Award]]|publisher=[[Henry W. Grady College of Journalism and Mass Communication]]|location=[[Athens, Georgia]]|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n|[[Carol Burnett Award for Achievement in Television]]\n|Entire Career\n| Herself\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|work=[[Golden Globe Awards]]|title=Carol Burnett to Receive the HFPA's First Award for Achievement in TV|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/carol-burnett-receive-hfpas-first-award-achievement-tv}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other honors===\n*1998: Grand Marshal of the 109th [[Rose Parade]] and the 84th [[Rose Bowl Game]] on New Year's Day <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tournamentofroses.com/rose-parade/theme-grand-marshal|title=THEME AND GRAND MARSHAL|publisher=Pasadena Tournament of Roses|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n*1999: The first honoree and presenter at second annual awards ceremony of the [[Back Stage West Garland Awards]]{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n*2003: [[Kennedy Center Honors]] recipient<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/pages/specialevents/honors|title=History of the Kennedy Center Honors|publisher=The Kennedy Center|accessdate=January 10, 2016}}</ref>\n*2009: Inducted into the [[California Hall of Fame]] at [[The California Museum for History, Women and the Arts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiamuseum.org/inductee/carol-burnett|title=Californiamuseum-Carol Burnett|publisher=California Museum|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n* 2014: Harvey Award recipient by [[The Jimmy Stewart Museum]] on August 12<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harley|first1=Tim|title=The Harvey Award Names Carol Burnett the 2014 Harvey Award Recipient!|url=http://jimmy.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2014-Harvey-PRESS-RELEASE.pdf|website=jimmy.org|publisher=The Jimmy Stewart Museum|accessdate=August 12, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505054827/http://jimmy.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2014-Harvey-PRESS-RELEASE.pdf|archivedate=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n*2019 : First recipient of the [[Golden Globes]], [[Carol Burnett Award|Carol Burnett Lifetime Achievement Award]] for Television which was named in her honor\n\n==Litigation==\n'''Burnett v. National Enquirer, Inc'''\n{{main|Burnett v. National Enquirer, Inc.}}\n\nIn 1976, a false report in the nation's leading supermarket [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]], ''[[The National Enquirer]],'' incorrectly implied that Burnett had been drunk and boisterous in public at a restaurant with U.S. Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] in attendance. The fact that both of her parents suffered from alcoholism made this a particularly sensitive issue to her.  Through years of persistent litigation, she won a judgment against the ''Enquirer'', in 1981.  Though the initial jury award of $1.6 million was reduced to $200,000 by a series of appeals, and the final settlement was out of court, the event was widely viewed as a historic victory for libel victims of [[tabloid journalism]].<ref name=\"carol_burnett_launches_1981_03_22_upi\">Scott, Vernon, [http://www.upi.com/Archives/1981/03/22/Carol-Burnett-launches-trial-balloon/6032354085200/ \"Carol Burnett launches trial balloon,\"], March 22, 1981, ''[[United Press International]] (UPI),'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"carol_burnett_given_1981_03_27_lindsey_nytimes\">Lindsey, Robert, [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/27/us/carol-burnett-given-1.6-million-in-suit-against-national-enquirer.html \"Carol Burnett given 1.6 million in suit against National Enquirer,\"], March 27, 1981, ''[[The New York Times]],'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"how_tabloids_1991_01_04_nytimes\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/01/04/news/how-the-supermarket-tabloids-stay-out-of-court.html \"How the Supermarket Tabloids Stay Out of Court,\"] January 4, 1991, ''[[The New York Times]],'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"tabloids_lies_1991_08_12_langberg_nytimes\">Langberg, Barry (libel attorney for Carol Burnett and others), opinion essay: [http://articles.latimes.com/1991-08-12/entertainment/ca-468_1_tabloids \"Tabloids' Lies Abuse the First Amendment,\"] August 12, 1991, ,\"], ''[[The Los Angeles Times]],'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"tabloid_law_pt1_1999_08_atlantic\">Beam, Alex, [https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1999/08/tabloid-law/377722/ \"Tabloid Law,\"] Part 1 of two parts, August 1999, ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]],'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"tabloid_law_pt2_1999_08_atlantic\">Beam, Alex, [https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1999/08/tabloid-law/377722/ \"Tabloid Law,\"] Part 2 of two parts, August 1999, ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]],'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"dr_phil_2016_07_14_wash_post\">Andrews, Travis M., [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/07/14/dr-phil-and-wife-robin-sue-the-national-enquirer-for-250000-million-citing-defamation/ \"Dr_ Phil and wife Robin sue the National Enquirer for $250 million, citing defamation,\"] July 14, 2016, ''[[The Washington Post]],'' retrieved January 1, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe former longtime chief editor Iain Calder in his book ''The Untold Story'' asserted that after the Burnett lawsuit, while under his leadership, the ''Enquirer'' worked hard to check the reliability of its facts and its sources.\n\n'''Carol Burnett and Whacko, Inc. vs. Twentieth Century Fox Film Corporation'''\n\nIn 2007, Burnett and Whacko, Inc. brought a suit against [[20th Century Fox|Twentieth Century Fox]] requesting at least $2 million in damages, alleging copyright infringement, violation of publicity rights, and misappropriation of name and likeness due to the use of her charwoman character and an altered version of \"Carol's Theme\", the theme song used in ''The Carol Burnett Show'', without her permission. The character and theme were used in the \"[[Peterotica]]\" episode of ''[[Family Guy]]'' when the characters discuss the cleanliness of a porn shop and one of them states it is so clean because Burnett works there as a janitor. The charwoman is shown mopping the floor in the porn shop, and the characters subsequently discuss Burnett's ear tug and make a crude comment about it. Burnett and her company requested that Fox remove all references to her, the theme and the character but the studio did not.<ref name=\"Reut20th\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-burnett/carol-burnett-sues-tvs-family-guy-cartoon-idUSN1624604020070317 |title=Carol Burnett sues TV's \"Family Guy\" cartoon |work=[[Reuters]] |date=March 16, 2007 |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Gun20th\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/celebrity/carol-burnett-v-family-guy |title=Carol Burnett v. \"Family Guy\" Comedian sues over porn shop spoof of beloved charwoman character |work=[[The Smoking Gun]] |date=March 16, 2018 |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> The suit was ruled in favor of the defendant because the bit was a parody, which is protected by the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]]. The judge agreed that the portrayal was crude but stated that the character Burnett created was far more creative than anything the ''Family Guy'' team could come up with on their own.<ref name=\"Overmind20th\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/family-guy/three-family-guy-episodes-got-fox-sued |title=The Three Family Guy Episodes That Got FOX Sued|work=[[Screener (website)|TV Overmind]] |last=Gerstenberger |first=Tim |date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{refbegin}}\n\n# {{note|1}} Book has no page numbers; source: Chapter V, ''They Called Them Spectaculars''\n\n{{refend}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NUXIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA364&lpg=PA364&dq=Burnett+was+born+in+San+Antonio,+Texas,+on+April+26,+1933#v=twopage&q=Burnett%20was%20born%20in%20San%20Antonio%2C%20Texas%2C%20on%20April%2026%2C%201933&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Television|editor=Horace Newcomb|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=[[Abingdon-on-Thames]]|year=2004|edition=2nd|isbn=978-1579583941|page=364}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VUxPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA88&lpg=PA88&dq=Elizabeth+Montgomery+as+Melissa+Morris#v=twopage&q=Elizabeth%20Montgomery%20as%20Melissa%20Morris&f=false|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|first=Herbie J.|last=Pilato|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield#Imprints|Taylor Trade Publishing]]|year=2013|location=[[Lanham, Maryland]]|isbn=978-1589798243|page=88}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1613740743|title=The Three Stooges Scrapbook|first1=Jeff|last1=Lenburg|first2=Joan Howard|last2=Maurer|first3=Greg|last3=Lenburg|publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]]|edition=Updated|year=2012|location=[[Chicago]]|isbn=978-1613740743|page=267}}\