{"title_page": "Lex Marinos", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Lex Marinos\n| image = Lex Marinos 2014.jpg\n| caption = Marinos in 2014\n| birth_name = Alexander Francis Marinos\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|2|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| restingplace =\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername =\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|comedian|director|writer|voice artist|media personality}}\n| yearsactive =1970\u2013present\n| spouse =\n| domesticpartner =\n| children =\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Francis Marinos''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OAM}}<ref name=\"AustralianGovernment_ItsanHonour_OAM_LexMarinos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=869768&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Search Australian Honours \u2013 Name: MARINOS, Alexander Francis|publisher=[[Government of Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]] www.itsanhonour.gov.au|accessdate=7 August 2009}}</ref> (born 1 February 1949) is a [[Greek Australians|Greek-Australian]] actor<ref>[[Who Do You Think You Are? (Australian TV series)]]</ref> Notable for his acting role as Bruno, the Italian son-in-law of Ted Bullpitt, on the 1980s Australian comedy television series ''[[Kingswood Country]]'' and as host of ''Late Night Legends'' on [[ABC Comedy|ABC2]], he was also a presenter on radio station Double Jay (2JJ, now [[Triple J]]) in the late 1970s with [[Ted Robinson (TV director)|Ted Robinson]].\n\n==Biography==\nMarinos was born on 1 February 1949 in [[Wagga Wagga]], New South Wales, the son of a [[Greeks|Greek]] immigrant father, Fotios (\"Frank\") Marinopoulos and [[Multiracial|mixed-raced]] mother, Anne Karofilis who was the daughter of Adonis (\"Tony\") Karofilis, a Greek migrant from [[Kassos]], [[Greece]] and Minnie Matheson, an [[Australians|Australian]] of distant [[English people|English]] descent, with descent going all the way back to English couple, Samuel Bradley, a convict, and Marian Mortimer, a free migrant who immigrated to [[Hobart]], [[Tasmania]] in the 19th century, and are Marinos's maternal great-great-great-grandparents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/video/26304067866/who-do-you-think-you-are-lex-marinos|title= Who Do You Think You Are?:Lex Marinos|publisher=www.sbs.com.au|date=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/stories/s2118726.htm|title=Unleashed \u2013 Lex Marinos |date=14 December 2007|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] www.abc.net.au/unleashed/stories/s2118726.htm|accessdate=7 August 2009}}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of New South Wales]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts#The B.A. and the B.A. .28Hons..29 in Australia and New Zealand|Bachelor of Arts degree with honours]] in [[Performing arts|Drama]].<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" /><ref name=\"UNSW_ADFAcademy_GuidetothePapersofLexMarinos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.adfa.edu.au/speccoll/finding_aids/marinos_lex.html|title=Reference Number: MS 327 Guide to the Papers of Lex Marinos|publisher=www.lib.adfa.edu.au [[Australian Defence Force Academy]]|accessdate=7 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Order of Australia ==\nMarinos was awarded the Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) for his services to the [[performing arts]]. He is also a former Deputy Chair of the Australia Council and the Community Cultural Development Fund of the Australia Council.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.celebrityspeakers.com.au/media-speakers/lex-marinos/ |title = Profile of Lex Marinos}} from www.celebrityspeakers.com.au</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he delivered the 10th annual [[Tom Brock Lecture]].<ref>[http://www.sporthistory.org/TomBrocklect.htm Tom Brock Lecture] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5vokYpha6?url=http://www.sporthistory.org/TomBrocklect.htm |date=18 January 2011 }} at the Australian Society for Sports History's website</ref>\nHe won with fellow cast at the [[Equity Ensemble Awards|Equity Awards]] for Most Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble In A Television Movie or Mini-Series.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===As actor===\n*''[[Glitch (TV series)|Glitch]]'' (2017) \u2013 Steve Tripidakis\n*''[[The Slap (TV series)|The Slap]]'' (2011) \u2013 Manolis\n*''Lunchtime'' (2005) (voice) \u2013 Narrator\n*''[[Pizza (TV series)|Pizza]]'' (2000) \u2013 Lawyer\n*''[[Water Rats (TV series)|Water Rats]]'' (1996) \u2013 Bellamy\n*''[[Bedevil]]'' (1993) \u2013 Dimitri<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[A Country Practice]]'' (1993)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[The Last Days of Chez Nous]]'' (1992) \u2013 Angelo<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Embassy (television series)|Embassy]]'' (1990) TV Series \u2013 Tariq Abdullah (1991\u201392)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Pandemonium (1987 film)|Pandemonium]]'' (1988) \u2013 Detective Sergeant Dick Dickerson\n*''[[City West]]'' (1984) TV Series \u2013 Tim Pappas\n*''[[Goodbye Paradise]]'' (1983) \u2013 Con<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Hoodwink (1981 film)|Hoodwink]]'' (1981) \u2013\n*''[[Kingswood Country]]'' (1980) \u2013 Bruno (1979\u20131984)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Cathy's Child]]'' (1979) \u2013 Con Havros<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Chopper Squad]]'' (1978)\n*''[[King's Men (television series)|King's Men]]''\n*''[[Matlock Police]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Scattergood: Friend of All]]'' (1975) TV Series\n*''[[The Aunty Jack Show]]'' (1972)\n*''[[The Rovers (TV series)|The Rovers]]''\n\n===As television director===\n*''[[A Country Practice]]'' (1994) TV Series<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Gillies and Company]]'' (1992) TV Series\n*''[[Boundaries of the Heart]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Hard Knuckle]]'' (1987) (TV)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Perhaps Love (1987 film)|Perhaps Love]]'' (1987) (TV)\n*''[[An Indecent Obsession]]'' (1985)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Remember Me (1985 film)|Remember Me]]'' (1985) (TV)\n*''[[Bodyline (miniseries)|Bodyline]]'' (1984) TV miniseries<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{EquityAward TVMiniSeriesTeleMovieCast 2010\u20132019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marinos, Lex}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Australian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Australian television directors]]\n[[Category:Australian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Australian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Australian actors of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Triple J announcers]]\n[[Category:People from Wagga Wagga]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Sydney Boys High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Lex Marinos\n| image = Lex Marinos 2014.jpg\n| caption = Marinos in 2014\n| birth_name = Alexander Francis Marinos\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|2|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| restingplace =\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername =\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|comedian|director|writer|voice artist|media personality}}\n| yearsactive =1970\u2013present\n| spouse =\n| domesticpartner =\n| children =\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Alexander Francis Marinos''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OAM}}<ref name=\"AustralianGovernment_ItsanHonour_OAM_LexMarinos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=869768&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Search Australian Honours \u2013 Name: MARINOS, Alexander Francis|publisher=[[Government of Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]] www.itsanhonour.gov.au|accessdate=7 August 2009}}</ref> (born 1 February 1949) is a [[Greek Australians|Greek-Australian]] actor<ref>[[Who Do You Think You Are? (Australian TV series)]]</ref> Notable for his acting role as Bruno, the Italian son-in-law of Ted Bullpitt, on the 1980s Australian comedy television series ''[[Kingswood Country]]'' and as host of ''Late Night Legends'' on [[ABC Comedy|ABC2]], he was also a presenter on radio station Double Jay (2JJ, now [[Triple J]]) in the late 1970s with [[Ted Robinson (TV director)|Ted Robinson]].\n\n==Biography==\nMarinos was born on 1 February 1949 in [[Wagga Wagga]], New South Wales, the son of a [[Greeks|Greek]] immigrant father, Fotios (\"Frank\") Marinopoulos and [[Multiracial|mixed-raced]] mother, Anne Karofilis who was the daughter of Adonis (\"Tony\") Karofilis, a Greek migrant from [[Kassos]], [[Greece]] and Minnie Matheson, an [[Australians|Australian]] of distant [[English people|English]] descent, with descent going all the way back to English couple, Samuel Bradley, a convict, and Marian Mortimer, a free migrant who immigrated to [[Hobart]], [[Tasmania]] in the 19th century, and are Marinos's maternal great-great-great-grandparents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/video/26304067866/who-do-you-think-you-are-lex-marinos|title= Who Do You Think You Are?:Lex Marinos|publisher=www.sbs.com.au|date=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/stories/s2118726.htm|title=Unleashed \u2013 Lex Marinos |date=14 December 2007|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] www.abc.net.au/unleashed/stories/s2118726.htm|accessdate=7 August 2009}}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of New South Wales]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts#The B.A. and the B.A. .28Hons..29 in Australia and New Zealand|Bachelor of Arts degree with honours]] in [[Performing arts|Drama]].<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" /><ref name=\"UNSW_ADFAcademy_GuidetothePapersofLexMarinos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.adfa.edu.au/speccoll/finding_aids/marinos_lex.html|title=Reference Number: MS 327 Guide to the Papers of Lex Marinos|publisher=www.lib.adfa.edu.au [[Australian Defence Force Academy]]|accessdate=7 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Order of Australia ==\nMarinos was awarded the Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) for his services to the [[performing arts]]. He is also a former Deputy Chair of the Australia Council and the Community Cultural Development Fund of the Australia Council.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.celebrityspeakers.com.au/media-speakers/lex-marinos/ |title = Profile of Lex Marinos}} from www.celebrityspeakers.com.au</ref>\n\nIn 2008 he delivered the 10th annual [[Tom Brock Lecture]].<ref>[http://www.sporthistory.org/TomBrocklect.htm Tom Brock Lecture] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5vokYpha6?url=http://www.sporthistory.org/TomBrocklect.htm |date=18 January 2011 }} at the Australian Society for Sports History's website</ref>\nHe won with fellow cast at the [[Equity Ensemble Awards|Equity Awards]] for Most Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble In A Television Movie or Mini-Series.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===As actor===\n*''[[Glitch (TV series)|Glitch]]'' (2017) \u2013 Steve Tripidakis\n*''[[The Slap (TV series)|The Slap]]'' (2011) \u2013 Manolis\n*''Lunchtime'' (2005) (voice) \u2013 Narrator\n*''[[Pizza (TV series)|Pizza]]'' (2000) \u2013 Lawyer\n*''[[Water Rats (TV series)|Water Rats]]'' (1996) \u2013 Bellamy\n*''[[Bedevil]]'' (1993) \u2013 Dimitri<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[A Country Practice]]'' (1993)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[The Last Days of Chez Nous]]'' (1992) \u2013 Angelo<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Embassy (television series)|Embassy]]'' (1990) TV Series \u2013 Tariq Abdullah (1991\u201392)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Pandemonium (1987 film)|Pandemonium]]'' (1988) \u2013 Detective Sergeant Dick Dickerson\n*''[[City West]]'' (1984) TV Series \u2013 Tim Pappas\n*''[[Goodbye Paradise]]'' (1983) \u2013 Con<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Hoodwink (1981 film)|Hoodwink]]'' (1981) \u2013\n*''[[Kingswood Country]]'' (1980) \u2013 Bruno (1979\u20131984)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Cathy's Child]]'' (1979) \u2013 Con Havros<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Chopper Squad]]'' (1978)\n*''[[King's Men (television series)|King's Men]]''\n*''[[Matlock Police]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Scattergood: Friend of All]]'' (1975) TV Series\n*''[[The Aunty Jack Show]]'' (1972)\n*''[[The Rovers (TV series)|The Rovers]]''\n\n===As television director===\n*''[[A Country Practice]]'' (1994) TV Series<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporation_Unleashed_LexMarinosBiography\" />\n*''[[Gillies and Company]]'' (1992) TV Series\n*''[[Boundaries of the Heart]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Hard Knuckle]]'' (1987) (TV)<ref name=\"AustralianBroadcastingCorporat